<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-12-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="486" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d486">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/519.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Attorney General</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-02"><hi rend="italic">December 2,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>The United States attorney of the western district of Texas has wired
                            that Madero may now appear in his district at any hour, and that he does
                            not deem evidence at hand against him sufficient to meet technical
                            requirements necessary to constitute violation of neutrality laws.
                            Before replying I would appreciate a full statement from Mexican embassy
                            as to the evidence for the use of the United States attorney.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wickersham</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>